<subSubSection id="C30FB2903526FFEAFF47FE61FBFFFDE6" pageId="5" pageNumber="361" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B3526FFEAFF47FE61FBFFFDE6" blockId="5.[151,1437,259,538]" pageId="5" pageNumber="361">
<emphasis id="B9613D093526FFEAFF47FE61FEE1FE51" bold="true" box="[199,334,403,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="361">Etymology.</emphasis>
The epithet honors an extinct indigenous civilization from the Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta, Caribbean region of 
<collectingCountry id="F302A18B3526FFEAFE09FE45FE55FE2D" box="[393,506,439,465]" name="Colombia" pageId="5" pageNumber="361">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, which inhabited the 
<collectingRegion id="49D12FF93526FFEAFD77FE45FC96FE2D" box="[759,825,439,465]" country="Colombia" name="Cesar" pageId="5" pageNumber="361">Cesar</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="49D12FF93526FFEAFCC7FE45FC6CFE2D" box="[839,963,439,465]" country="Colombia" name="Magdalena" pageId="5" pageNumber="361">Magdalena</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="49D12FF93526FFEAFB81FE4AFBD2FE2D" box="[1025,1149,439,466]" country="Colombia" name="La Guajira" pageId="5" pageNumber="361">La Guajira</collectingRegion>
departments, and whose descendants currently correspond to the Arhuaco, Kankuamo, Kogui and Wiwa peoples. To be treated as an arbitrary combination of letters, and hence without the need to agree in gender with the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
